result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacob Jeffry Stilwell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Cocaine/Coca(2nd+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(c).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Court grants 191 days credit.
Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Defendant IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

superMiscConds.notes: Standard court costs waived.  DNA Surcharge to be paid as a condition of Extended Supervision.

AODA assessment, follow through with any treatment recommended.  Maintain absolute sobriety.  Comply with random urine screens.  No use or possession of alcohol or illegal drugs, CBD products, vaping products, or drug paraphernalia.  No use or possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription. Any valid prescriptions must be taken only in the manner they are prescribed.

Follow through with any assessments, evaluations, treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent.   No presence on any premises whose primary business is serving or selling alcohol (i.e bars, taverns, or liquor stores).  
Defendant to complete "Thinking for Change" class.  
Do not drive or operate a motor vehicle without a valid license.

Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not yet provided, immediately if in custody otherwise within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department.
If Probation/Extended Supervision is revoked and/or a prison term ordered, outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  Collections may include income assignment.
